    <div class="container">
        <!-- SECTION 1: WHAT IS DAILY WAGE CALCULATOR? -->
        <section class="section">
            <h2 class="section-title">What is Daily Wage Calculator?</h2>
            
            <figure class="screenshot-container">
                <img src="screenshots/02-daily-wage-calc-expanded.png" alt="Daily Wage Calculator interface showing configuration table with salary proration, EOS eligibility, and unpaid leave settings" class="screenshot">
                <figcaption>Daily Wage Calculator configuration interface displaying three calculation contexts with their respective day counts and salary components</figcaption>
            </figure>

            <div class="card">
                <p style="margin-bottom: var(--spacing);">
                    <span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">
                        The Daily Wage Calculator is a flexible and customizable system that provides a unified method for calculating daily wages across multiple payroll scenarios including salary proration, leave encashment, and unpaid leave deductions.
                    </span>
                </p>
                
                <p style="margin-bottom: var(--spacing);">
                    <span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">
                        This feature allows organizations to select calculation bases (calendar days, working days, or custom days) and choose which salary components to factor into calculations, ensuring compliance with regional labor laws while maintaining flexibility for organizational policies.
                    </span>
                </p>

                <div class="alert alert-info">
                    <strong>Strategic Context:</strong> 
                    <span class="citation" data-source="zendesk" data-ref="14243704039185">
                        Most UAE and KSA companies use 30 custom days to align with labor law requirements, while the system accommodates varying month lengths (31 days in January, 28 days in February) through flexible calculation methods.
                    </span>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3 class="section-subtitle">Platform Coverage</h3>
            <div class="grid grid-3">
                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-title">Salary Proration</div>
                    <p><span class="citation" data-source="validation" data-ref="plan_salary_proration_config">Adjusts employee salary proportionally based on actual days worked, affecting first salary and end-of-service settlement</span></p>
                    <div class="formula">
                        <span class="citation" data-source="screenshot" data-ref="02-daily-wage-calc-expanded.png">
                            30.45 days (custom)
                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-title">EOS Leave Encashment</div>
                    <p><span class="citation" data-source="validation" data-ref="plan_eos_config_primary">Calculates leave encashment values for end-of-service settlements with configurable leave types</span></p>
                    <div class="formula">
                        <span class="citation" data-source="screenshot" data-ref="02-daily-wage-calc-expanded.png">
                            22 days (working days)
                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-title">Unpaid Leave Deductions</div>
                    <p><span class="citation" data-source="validation" data-ref="plan_leaves_unpaid_policy">Calculates daily deductions for unpaid leave taken by employees</span></p>
                    <div class="formula">
                        <span class="citation" data-source="screenshot" data-ref="02-daily-wage-calc-expanded.png">
                            30 days (custom)
                        </span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

